SIMPLE: penitent
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Penitent
<hw>Pen"i*tent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>p⟦eacute⟧nitent</ets>, L. <ets>paenitens</ets>, <ets>-entis</ets>,
<ets>poenitens</ets>, p. pr. of <ets>paenitere</ets>,
<ets>poenitere</ets>, to cause to repent, to repent; prob. akin to
<ets>poena</ets> punishment. See <er>Pain</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Feeling pain or sorrow on account of sins or offenses; repentant;
contrite; sincerely affected by a sense of guilt, and resolved on
amendment of life.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Be <qex>penitent</qex>, and for thy fault contrite.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The proud he tamed, the <qex>penitent</qex> he cheered.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Doing penance.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Penitent</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Penitent
<hw>Pen"i*tent</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who repents of
sin; one sorrowful on account of his transgressions.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One under church censure, but admitted to penance;
one undergoing penance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>One under the direction of a confessor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Penitents</xex> is an appellation given to certain
fraternities in Roman Catholic countries, distinguished by their habit,
and employed in charitable acts.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Penitential</ent>⟦br⟧
